<DOC><DOCNO> AP890216-0235 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 0139EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     02-16 0783</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0816</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.S. industry is using more of its capacitythan at any other time in nearly a decade, the government said in areport that showed operating rates approaching levels that couldworsen inflation.   The stock and bond markets were not alarmed by Wednesday'sreport. Bond prices rose modestly and the Dow Jones average of 30industrials climbed 22.68 points to 2,303.93. The dollar fellsharply but later made back most of its losses.   The Federal Reserve Board said January's operating rate of 84.4percent of capacity was unchanged from December, for which thefigure was revised upward from an earlier estimate of 84.2 percent.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Business inventories rose 0.9 percent inDecember and sales increased at almost the same pace despite abuildup in stockpiles of unsold autos as car purchases lagged, thegovernment said.   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that inventories held onshelves and back lots rose to a seasonally adjusted $760.6 billionin December, while sales reached $508.2 billion.   December's 0.9 percent increase in inventories followed a 0.4percent increase in November. Sales, meanwhile, rose 0.8 percent inDecember following a 0.4 percent increase in November.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Oil imports last month surged to the highest ratesince 1980 as domestic production fell and consumption rose,reviving fears that foreign producers may soon control more thanhalf of U.S. oil supplies, energy analysts said.   The American Petroleum Institute, which represents major oilproducers and refiners, said Wednesday that U.S. crude oilproduction fell to 7.9 million barrels a day, a 3.4 percent dropfrom January 1988.   Alaskan oil production, which in recent years offset declines inother parts of the United States, slipped for the second straightmonth with no major new oil fields tapped. About a quarter of U.S.oil comes from Alaska.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Consumer activist Ralph Nader called onPresident Bush and Congress to force rich people, stock traders andcorporations, rather than average taxpayers, to pay for the savingsand loan crisis.   ``If the bankers and the bureaucrats think they're going toresolve this massive savings and loan crime on the backs of tens ofmillions of ordinary U.S. taxpayers as part of their littleinner-Washington club deliberation, they're wrong,'' Nader saidWednesday.   Bush last week announced a proposal to spend $200 billion overthe next 30 years _ about half of it from general tax revenues _ tosell or close 350 insolvent institutions and meet governmentcommitments made last year in the rescue of another 205 Sandamp;Ls.</TEXT><DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Union Carbide Corp. became a takeovertarget after the 1984 Bhopal gas leak depressed its stock, and someanalysts said the chemical giant could face another raid with thecloud of Bhopal lifted.   But others said Wednesday the surge in Carbide stock incited bythe settlement that was announced Tuesday could help protect thecompany from a takeover by making it more expensive to acquire.   Carbide agreed Tuesday to a Supreme Court of India ruling thatordered the company to pay $470 million by March 31 to settle allclaims stemming from the Bhopal gas leak, which left more than 3,300people dead.</TEXT><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The militant Machinists union announced overwhelmingsupport for a strike against Eastern Airlines next month unless acontract is signed, while the carrier charged that an illegal workslowdown has backed up 19 aircraft and delayed flights.   In another development Wednesday, the union contended thatEastern management has brought recruitment of possiblestrikebreakers to its home turf.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A ``supercomputer on a chip'' developed by IntelCorp. and hailed as a technical marvel by engineers will be offeredas the basis for a new line of high-speed computers, a senior Intelexecutive said.   Intel's N-10 chip was introduced Wednesday at the InternationalSolid State Circuits Conference, the world chip industry's biggestresearch meeting of the year.   The United States continues to dominate in processor chips _ thebrains of computers _ even though Japan has taken over most of theworld market for memory chips.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   Blue chips led the way as the stock market rallied Wednesday,breaking out of a week-long slump. The Dow Jones average of 30industrials climbed 22.68 points to 2,303.93.   The dollar retreated across a broad front before recovering somelost ground. Gold prices fell.   A change in perceptions about the near-term prospects forinterest rates helped lift bond prices.   Energy futures prices broke through an important price barrierand posted significant gains; soybeans rose modestly; platinumsurged; and cattle and pork futures were down slightly.</TEXT></DOC>